CINNAMON ROLL MUFFINS

Good Morning!! Start your day with a batch of delicious Cinnamon Roll Muffins. Like a cinnamon roll, these muffins are layered with cinnamon sugar/sweetener and topped with a cream cheese frosting. Quick and easy to make. No waiting for dough to rise like a traditional cinnamon roll - make and ready to eat in under 30 minutes.

Ingredients:
MUFFINS:
1 pkg  @kawaiitreatsandeats Almond-Free Cake Base Mix (USE CODE: DEB10)
4 eggs
6 Tbsp butter
3 oz cream cheese
2 Tbsp brown sweetener
1 Tbsp vanilla extract
CINNAMON FILLING:
1/2 cup brown sweetener
2 Tbsp butter, melted
2 tsp cinnamon
CREAM CHEESE FROSTING:
2 oz butter, softened
2 oz cream cheese, softened
3/4 cups powdered sweetener
1/2 tsp vanilla extract

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.  Line a 12-well muffin pan with cupcake liners.
2. In a microwave safe mixing bowl, heat butter and cream cheese until almost melted.
3. Remove from microwave and mix well (until smooth).
4. Add in brown sweetener to warm butter mixture, and mix until sweetener is dissolved (there will be some tiny clumps of sweetener).
5. Add eggs and vanilla extract, mix well.
6. Add in cake mix and mix until just combined.
7. Make the cinnamon filling: mix 1/2 cup of brown sweetener, 2 tablespoons melted butter, and and 2 teaspoons of cinnamon. Set aside.
8. Add about 2 tablespoons of cupcake batter to each cupcake cup. Press the batter so that it fills the bottom of each liner.
9. Sprinkle each with cinnamon sugar mixture over the pancake batter in each liner.
10. Top with remaining cupcake batter over the cinnamon mixture.
11 . Bake 18-20 minutes, checking in between to rotate pans (if necessary). Bake until just set and a toothpick comes out clean. Don't over bake.
12. Remove from oven and top with cream cheese frosting.
13. Enjoy! Best when warm

CREAM CHEESE FROSTING:
In a bowl, mix the softened butter and cream cheese. Add in the extract. Mix well.
Add in the powdered sweetener and whisk until smooth. For a thinner frosting add in a bit of heavy whipping cream.

GINGERSNAP SPICED PECANS

You must try these toasted pecans that are covered with a sweet and crispy coating that is bursting with the flavors of gingersnaps (gingerbread). Cinnamon, cloves, ginger, and a hint of molasses! Perfect side dish for your holiday party! They are so easy to make and everyone will love them. A great little finger food to have around this time of year.

FOLLOW ME for more delicious recipes!

Ingredients:
10 oz pecan halves
1/2 tsp blackstrap molasses
1/2 tsp @swervesweetie brown sweetener
1/2 tsp ground ginger
1/2 tsp ground cinnamon
1/8 tsp ground cloves
1 Tbsp + 1 tsp water

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 200F.
2. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper or foil. If using foil, spray with coconut or avocado oil.
3. In a mixing bowl, combine the brown sweetener, black strap molasses, ginger, cinnamon, cloves and water. Mix well (the mixture should be a thick pour-able consistency).
4. Gently stir in the pecan and mix to coat.
5. Place your coated pecans in a single layer on the prepared baking sheet.
6. Bake for 1 hour, stirring every 20 minutes.
7. Remove from the oven. Allow pecans to cool completely.

OVEN ROASTED TOMATO BISQUE

This homemade Oven Roasted Tomato Bisque will hit the spot on a cold wintery day. You will need to get out your dutch oven for this. It's made by oven roasting cherry tomatoes, onion, and garlic that has been seasoned with crack black pepper and drizzled with olive oil.  Remove the veggies from the oven and bring to your stove top and add in vegetable broth and season again with salt, pepper, and celery seed. Simmer for a few minutes then blend with a hand blender. Right before serving add in mascarpone cheese - making a luscious creamy bisque that will warm your heart. Serve this soup at your holiday dinner - it can be made ahead and reheated. And honestly it gets better as it sets - I highly recommend making a day ahead.

20 oz cherry or grape tomatoes
1 onion, chopped
3 cloves garlic
3 Tbsp @californiaoliveranch Garlic Infused Extra Virgin Olive Oil
cracked black pepper to taste
salt to taste
20 oz vegetable broth
3 to 4 oz @lelgioiosocheese mascarpone cheese
1/4 tsp celery seed

1. In a dutch oven, place tomatoes, chopped onion, and garlic cloves. Season with cracked black pepper and salt.
2. Drizzle garlic infused olive oil over the veggies.
3. Cover the dutch oven, place in a 400 degree oven. Roast for 30 to 40 minutes or until tomatoes have cracked.
4. Remove from oven and let set for 10 minute.
5. Add vegetable broth. Season with celery seed (more salt and pepper if need be). Simmer for 15 minutes.
6. Blend with hand blender until smooth.
7. Right before serving, stir in mascarpone cheese.

CRAB STUFFED SHRIMP

Y'all are going to want to make these Crab Stuffed Shrimp! These decadent shrimp are stuffed with crab and seasoned cracker crumbs and baked in a buttery wine sauce.

I used almond flour crackers, making the stuffing lowcarb and glutenfree but feel free to use whatever crackers you like (Ritz, saltines,etc.). And don't fear, they really are pretty easy to make. To save a step or two, I buy already peeled and deviened  and aI make ahead and then freeze before baking. Then on the day you are ready to bake them, place the frozen shrimp in the baking dish and pour on the wine sauce. Pop in the oven and enjoy! You and your guests will LOVE these Crab Stuffed Shrimp! Enjoy!

Ingredients:
2 Tbsp butter
2 finely chopped green onions
1 clove garlic, minced
1/3 cup minced green bell pepper
1 jalapeno pepper, minced (optional)
1/4 tsp garlic powder
1 Tbsp dijon mustard
1 dash cayenne pepper
1/2 cup low crab cracker crumbs (I used @simplemills almond crackers)
1/4 cup mayonnaise
1 egg
2 Tbsp fresh parsley
1/2 juiced lemon
3 cans lump crab meat, drained
1 lb peeled, deveined, tails on jumbo shrimp
1/4 cup butter, melted
1/4 cup dry white wine (or lemon juice)

Directions:
1. Make the stuffing - melt 2 Tbsp butter in a skillet and then add in the green onions  and peppers, and saute for 3-4 minutes. Then, add garlic and cook for about a minute. Remove from heat and let cool to room temperature.
2. In a separate bowl, add cracker crumbs and vegetable mixture (including all the butter drippings). Mix in 1 egg and mayonnaise.
3. Prepare the shrimp, cut along the length of the inside of the shrimp without cutting all the way through. Flatten the shrimp with the tail pointing up and place in a baking dish with the newly cut side facing up.
4. Scoop a tablespoon of stuffing into a mound on the shrimp’s flat part. Then, bake for about 20 minutes. (Note: Can be frozen prior to baking - bake time will be longer if frozen).
5. In a microwave safe bow), melt 1/4 cup butter. Remove from microwave, stir in 1/4 cup dry white wine. Pour over shrimp. Bake for 20 minutes, or until shrimp are just pink.

ASPARAGUS AU GRATIN

This Cheesy Asparagus au Gratin is sure to wow your family and guests this holiday season! Use the best ingredients to make this - using the freshest asparagus and good quality cheeses. To make you simply blanch the asparagus, place in a casserole dish, top with a decadent cheese sauce, and then bake in the oven.

Make Ahead Tips:
* Buy your asparagus a few days in advance:  To keep asparagus fresh, trim bottoms, place in a cup or tall glass that has 1/2 inch of water in it, lightly cover the asparagus with a light weight plastic bag or plastic wrap.
* Blanch asparagus and store, covered, in the fridge. Make cheese sauce ahead, store in fridge, then warm on the stove top. When ready to make, assemble and bake.

1 lb asparagus, cleaned and trimmed
3 Tbsp butter
1 shallot, minced
1 cup heavy cream
1/8 tsp freshly grated nutmeg
salt and fresh cracked black pepper to taste
1/2 cup Parmesan cheese
1 cup shredded Fontina or  Gruyere cheese

Topping:
1/4 cup Parmesan cheese
1 tsp Sweet paprika

1. Heat oven to 375 degrees F.
2. Blanch asparagus: Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add the asparagus to the boiling water and cook until bright green and crisp-tender, about 3 minutes. Using a slotted spoon, transfer the asparagus to an ice water bath. Remove and drain on paper towels.
3. Arrange the asparagus in a buttered 13 x 9-inch baking dish
4. Make your sauce, in a medium size sauce pan, melt butter, add in shallot, cook until softened.
5. Slowly pour in heavy cream and heat until a light simmer. Stir in cheeses and heat until just melted.
6. Pour cheese sauce over the asparagus. Top with parmesan cheese and sweet paprika.
7. Bake for 30 minutes until bubbly.

Serve and Enjoy!

EGGPLANT ROLLATINI

Cooked eggplant stuffed with a cheesy filling and rolled up into individual servings. Then baked in a rich tomato sauce. No breading, no frying, just the most delicious lowcarb Italian meal that the whole family will love!

Some struggle with thinking that Italian food is not lowcarb! There are so many classic Italian dishes that you can make that don't involve pasta, breading or frying. This is one dish that is truly lowcarb in it's traditional form. Enjoy!

Ingredients:
2 large eggplants
1 cup whole-milk @belgiosocheese ricotta cheese
1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese
1 egg
1/4 tsp salt
1/2 tsp black pepper
2 Tbsp fresh chopped parsley (or 1 Tbsp dried parsley)
1 Tbsp fresh chopped basil (or 1 tsp dried basil)
2 1/2 cups tomato sauce (see my quick sauce recipe a few posts back)
3/4 cup mozzarella cheese, divided
1 Tbsp @californiaoliveranch EVOO

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees F.
2. Remove stems from eggplants. Cut each eggplant lengthwise into 1/4-inch thick slices.
3. Place the sliced eggplant on paper towels, salt both sides and let sit to sweat (about 10 minutes). Pat dry with paper towel.
4. Drizzle and brush olive oil onto a baking pan. Lay the eggplant and on the pan and bake 5 to 10 minutes. Remove and let cool.
5. Make the filling by mixing together, in a mixing bowl, the ricotta cheese, 1/4 cup of mozzarella cheese, Parmesan cheese, egg, basil, parsley, salt and pepper.
6. Spread a layer of tomato sauce on the bottom of a baking dish.
7. After the eggplant has cooled, spoon a heaping tablespoon of ricotta filling on to each eggplant slice, roll the eggplant slices and place in the baking dish on top of the sauce.
8. Spoon the remaining sauce over the eggplant and sprinkle with 1/2 cup mozzarella cheese. Cover with foil and bake 30 minutes, uncover and bake for 10minutes until bubbly and cheese is melted.

PRIME RIB SOUP

This a great soup recipe to make when you have leftover prime rib. I make the day after with fresh veggies and the prime rib. If you want to make at a later time, I recommend you cut the meat off the bone and into cubes, then please in an air tight container in the freezer for when you are ready to make. The base of this soup made with good beef stock, red wine, and a touch of (sugar-free) ketchup. I know this sounds odd, but trust me that little bit of sweetness and tomato from the ketchup is the secrete to this delicious soup.

4 cups cubed cooked prime rib
1 Tbsp olive oil
1 large onion, diced
3 stalks celery, diced
2 carrots, peeled and diced
5 cups beef stock (or 5 cups water plus 2 Tbsp beef soup base)
1 cup dry red wine (or auju*)
1/4 cup sugar-free ketchup
1 cup chopped fresh green beans
2 large potatoes, peeled and diced
1 zucchini, peeled and diced
salt and ground black pepper to taste

*when I make my prime rib, I whip together a quick red wine au jus with the drippings to serve with the prime rib. I reserve a cup (or as much as I can) and use this instead of the wine. If you don't have a full cup, just add red wine to your reserves to make 1 cup. See note below on how to make.

1. In a large pot over medium heat, heat olive oil. Add onions, carrots, and celery and cook until soft, 5 minutes. Add in beef stock (or water mixed with beef soup base), red wine, and ketchup. Lower heat to a simmer.
2. Add in green beans, potatoes, and zucchini. Simmer on low for about 30-45 minutes or until vegetables are almost soft.
3. Add in prime rib. Season with salt and pepper. Simmer on a low simmer for another 30-45 minutes (simmer very low you don't want to boil - this keeps the prime rib from over cooking).

* To make Red Wine Au Jus:
Remove the prime rib from the roast pan, and then  place the roasting pan on top of the stove. Turn heat the med-high, add in 1/2 stick of butter to the pan and use a wooden spoon to stir and scrape the bottom of the pan. Add the 2 cups beef stock and 1 cup red wine and cook until the liquid is reduced by half, about 20 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.

Cheesy Cloud Biscuits

I jotted down this Cloud Biscuit recipe about 5 years ago when looking for a lowcarb biscuit option. My cousin told me about these biscuits, however he didn't have the measurements so all I know is that we came up it from a google search. :) They are super easy to make and most likely you have all the ingredients in your pantry (assuming you are an almond flour lover like me).

I'm calling them Cheesy Cloud Biscuits because depending on the type if cheese you use, the biscuits give off different vibes. Using mozzarella cheese I got a light airy Cheesy Cloudy vibe, using just cheddar cheese with a bit of garlic powder I get the Red Lobster Cheddar Bay Biscuit vibe, and if I use a combination of cheddar and shredded Parmesan you get a Brazilian Cheese Bread vibe.

LIKE & SAVE THIS RECIPE - You WILL want to make these!

1 cup Almond Flour
1 tsp Baking Powder
1 Tbsp Heavy Cream
1 Egg
1 cup Grated Mozzarella Cheese (or Cheddar, Parmesan)
Add-ins (optional: garlic powder, chives, cayenne, herbs, etc.)

1. Preheat your oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit and line a baking sheet with parchment paper.
2. In a mixing bowl, add the almond flour and baking powder. Stir to combine.
3. Add the cream to the dry ingredients and mix to combine. Then add the egg. Stir to combine until mixture is moist but do not over mix.
4. Fold in the grated cheese.
5. Drop about 1/4 cup of dough per biscuit onto the parchment lined baking sheet (or baking dish)
Place the baking sheet/dish in the preheated oven and bake at 350 degrees 12-15 minutes or until they are golden. Serve immediately.

Lowcarb Fried Veggies

Sunday afternoon football calls for delicious snacks! I'll be serving up these quick fried veggies. Our favorite veggies to fry are onions, mushrooms, zucchini, and bell peppers. Coated in a egg and bread crumbs made from leftover egg white protein bread. I made the bread crumbs by pulsing leftover psmf rolls (from earlier this week), and then baked in the oven for minutes.

Serve as is or with your favorite dipping sauce (ranch, hot sauce, blue cheese, horseradish dip. etc.)

SAVE & LIKE THIS RECIPE - Keep on file for Super Bowl Sunday!

Ingredients:
Vegetables (of your choice)
Homemade #psmf bread crumbs (see below)
Avocado Oil
Salt & Pepper

Make Bread crumbs: Cut up left over egg white bread and place in a food chopper. Pulse into fine crumbs. Spread the crumbs on a baking sheet and bake at 350 degrees for about 10 minutes until they become dry and crunchy. Don't over bake. Set aside and let cool.

1. Cut veggies into bite size pieces.
2. In a bowl mix together 1 egg and 1 teaspoon of water to make an egg wash.
3. Place bread crumbs in a shallow bowl.
4. Dip each veggie in the egg wash and then into the bread crumbs.
5.  Heat oil in a skillet or dutch oven to 375°.
6. Carefully add the vegetables to the hot oil. Work in batches so the vegetables don't over crowd the pan. Cook forabout 30 seconds on each, until golden brown.
7. Remove the vegetables from the skillet to a plate lined with paper towels to drain and cool. Season with salt and pepper.
Enjoy!

Note:  You can make ahead and then reheat in the oven, air fryer, or toaster oven.

Blueberries in brownies? Yes, yes, yes! Adding blueberries to your brownies makes moist, decadent, super delicious brownies. And blueberries are sooo good for you!

I fold fresh blueberries through the batter and then add more on top, as soon as the brownies come out of the oven. Best part - these are gluten-free, nut-free (no almond flour), lowcarb, and keto friendly. Made with @think.eat.live Sunflour, dark cocoa, blueberries, and a combination of sweeteners (Allulose is important here for texture).

If you are brownie lover, you NEED to make these.

Ingredients:
1 1/2 cup Sunflour, @Think.Eat.Live

1 tsp baking powder
1/2 tsp salt
125g Allulose sweetener, @RxSugar
125g granular monkfruit sweetener, @lakanto

Cheesy Escarole Dip with Meat Crisps

Warm Cheesy Escarole Dip is a twist on the party-favorite spinach dip that we know. Hearty escarole replaces the spinach in this pub favorite appetizer. Serve up with @carnivorecrisps Chicken & Beef crisps for a super lowcarb protein packed snack! Escarole can be a tad bitter so I cook until wilted in lightly salted water to take the bitterness away. Drain real well and then whip it in a food processor with the cream cheese, mayo, sour cream, and garlic. Fold in the other cheeses and red pepper flakes.

Ingredients:
6 cups fresh chopped escarole
1/2 cup shredded mozzarella cheese
1/2 cup shredded provolone cheese
 3 Tbsp grated Parmesan cheese
4 oz cream cheese softened

1/2 cup sour cream
1 clove garlic minced or 1 tsp of garlic powder
1/4 teaspoon red pepper flakes

3. In a food processor, chopper, add cream cheese and drained escarole. Pulse a few times, add in mayo, sour cream, and garlic. Pulse until smooth, about 1 minute.

I know you've all seen, and mostly likely have eaten a Taco Salad .. but hear me out .... I'm picky about my ground beef taco meat. And want my salad to be delicious! I like to know what's going in the meat (hence, no packaged seasoning), and I like it to not be greasy, and good soft texture. Years and more years ago, I saw a method where you cook/boil/simmer the taco meat in water (maybe you all already know this, but I didn't) - it results in a soft texture (almost velvety mouth feel) like you get in most Mexican restaurants, it's not greasy, and full of flavor. I'm no pro here, but we LOVE the ground beef cooked this way. I've been doing it this way for at least 10 years.

Ingredients:
2 lb ground beef
1 Large onion, diced
6 cloves garlic, diced
1 Tbsp black pepper
2 Tbsp chili powder
1/4 tsp cayenne pepper
1 to 2 tsp salt
2 tsp dried oregano
2 tsp cumin
1 1/2 cups of water*

*You need the water to completely cover the ground beef in the pan. I use a large deep skillet. If you have a deeper pan, you will probably need more water. But I find that somewhere between 1 to 1 1/2 cups of water is about right for a large deep sided skillet.

1. Dice onions and garlic.
2. Place ground beef, onions, and garlic in the pan.
3. Cover with water, just enough to cover the meat about 1 1/2 cups. (Don't worry it will seem like alot of water, but trust me, it works!)
4. Add spices (black pepper, chili powder, cayenne, cumin, oregano, and salt).
5. Mash up with mixture until the beef is broken up into small pieces.
6. Every 20 minutes or so, mash the meat so it doesn't clump together.
7. Simmer for 1.5 to 2 hours on medium-low heat, with no lid, until most of the liquid has evaporated. Adjust seasonings if need be.
8. Drain off fat before serving.

Remember, cook slow and low for best results.

I found the perfect lowcarb pasta recipe over at @fatkitchenblog. It is made with lupin flour, almond flour, tapico flour, and a few other ingredients. It turned out perfect! The texture is great, it was so easy to roll and cut. And is delicious! I used my hand crank pasta machine to roll and cut into linguine. It makes 5 servings. So I dried 4 of the 5 to make later. You can make whatever shapes you want. I'm definitely making lasagna noodles and ravioli next.

She goes quite in depth how to make the pasta. I will give you my quick run down on how I make it and the brand of ingredients I use.

Ingredients:
150 grams (1 cup +3 Tbsp) Lupina Lupin Flour (Lupina brand)
22 grams (3 Tbsp) Tapioca Flour (@bobsredmill)
24 grams (3 Tbsp) Blanched Almond Flour (@bluediamond)
1 tsp Allulose (@RxSugar)
1/4 tsp + 2 pinches Salt (@redmondrealsalt)
1/2 tsp Xanthan Gum (add 1/4 tsp more if hand-rolling pasta)
3 Large Eggs, room temperature (150 grams)
Silicone Baking Mat @gourmeteasyonline

Directions:
1. In a bowl, whisk together the lupin flour, tapioca flour, almond flour, salt and xanthan gum (I  used the extra 1/4 tsp she recommends since I hand-rolled my pasta).
2. Make a nest (aka as a well) in the dried mixture. Add the eggs, and use a fork to break up the eggs, keeping the flour wall intact. Continue working with the fork to incorporate the flour into the eggs.
3. Once the dough comes together, place it on a silicone mat. Using your hands, knead the dough for 8 to 10 minutes. The dough will feel dry but it will come together. Once the dough turns to a nice smooth ball, cover with plastic wrap, and let rest about 30 minutes.
4. Cut the dough into pieces (I did 6), set the dough piece onto a countertop and keep covered.
5. Run the dough through the pasta roller on level 7, then level 6, down to level 3. You should have a nice long pasta sheet at this point. (Note: level 1 is the thickest setting on my pasta roller).
6. Run the pasta sheet through the pasta cutting end. Lay on the sheet pan. If dough is sticky, sprinkle a bit of tapioca flour on the pasta sheets before cutting.
7. The pasta is ready to boil. The pasta should be cooked after 3 to 5 min.

What is a garlic scape? Garlic scapes are the long tender stem/flower bud of the hardneck garlic plant. The scape is removed in late June to encourage the bulbs to thicken up. They look like a long curly green bean.

🧄Garlic scapes are a bit milder than a garlic clove. Making them perfect to eat straight up sauted or wrapped in bacon!!

In then northeast and Canada garlic scapes are readily available at local farmers markets during the early summer months. I'm not sure about the other parts of the country. If you see them near you, let us know in the comments.

Ingredients:
🥓 6 slices of bacon (I used uncured bacon, that I picked up the @troymarket)
🧄 6 garlic scapes (also from the farmers market)

Directions:
1. Cut each garlic scape in half. Leaving a curled piece and a straight piece
2. Slice bacon in half
3. Tightly wrap each scape with a half slice piece of bacon, spiraling down the scape as you go. If bacon is thick you can secure with a toothpick.
4. In a pan, on the stove top, over medium heat, cook the scapes until the bacon browns/crisps on one side and then turn over and cook the other side until bacon is brown/crisp.  I like the scape to be charred and slightly soft. If scape is not softened yet, turn the heat to low and allow to cook more.
5. Remove from the pan, drain on paper towels.
6. Serve & Enjoy!
Note: These reheat well in a pan or in the oven.

My son has me addicted to this Garlic Confit. Have you ever had it? It's AMAZING - it's a whole different world in taste - Garlic confit is simply cloves of garlic cooked slowly in olive oil. The slow cooking mellows the flavor while olive oil adds richness. It is delicious on bread, pasta, pizza, soups and sauces. I've been putting it on low carb @grainfreeplanet (formerly California Country Gal) Bread for snacking- it spreads like butter! And is so delicious!

You really only need three things to make the confit garlic: garlic cloves, olive oil, and a baking dish. You can experiment with additional flavors. We used bay leaves, rosemary, and red pepper flakes. You could add in sprig of rosemary or any fresh herb.

FYI: The French word "confit" means to preserve - "Confit is any type of food that is cooked slowly over a long period as a method of preservation". Food can be slowly cooked in any liquid, oil or water at a lower temperature. Can be done with meats, egg yolks, fruits, vegetables, garlic, etc.

Have you ever done this method?

To make Garlic Confit:
* 3 to 4 heads of garlic
* 1 1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil @californiaoliveranch
* 2 bay leaves
* 1/2 tsp dried rosemary 
* red pepper flakes

1. Preheat oven to 200 degrees.
2. Peel the garlic cloves (you could buy already peeled garlic - but fresh is best!)
3. Placed the peeled garlic cloves in a baking dish.
4. Add in enough olive oil to cover the garlic cloves (you may need or less, depending on the size of your baking dish).
5. Add bay leaves and red pepper flakes (or whatever herbs you like).
6. Bake until garlic is soft and the oil is golden (not brown), about 2 hours.

Serve with Sourdough Bread

This is my go-to homemade Pumpkin Bread l, and I always get rave reviews. It's quick and easy to make and wonderfully moist, spicy and it's loaded with walnuts (totally optional, but really so delicious!). This pumpkin bread is made with almond flour, pumpkin, sweetener of choice, all the favorite fall spices, and walnuts. It's even better the next day after all the flavors have a chance to meld. 

Pumpkin Bread with Walnuts 
Makes: 1 loaf (12 servings)

Ingredients:
1 cup canned pumpkin (not pumpkin pie filling!)
4 eggs
3/4 cup butter, melted
1/3 cup unsweetened vanilla almond milk
1 teaspoon vanilla
2 cups blanched super fine almond flour
1/2 cup coconut flour
4 teaspoon baking powder
1/2 cup Allulose Stevia Blend Sweetener*
2 Tablespoon Swerve Sweetener, Brown 

1 teaspoon  ground cinnamon
1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
1 4 teaspoon ground ginger
1/8 teaspoon ground cloves
1/8 teaspoon salt
1/2 cup chopped walnuts, divided

*Use any 1:1 sugar alternative for keto/low carb, coconut sugar for Paleo, or regular sugar (for non-keto)

Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line a 9x5 inch loaf pan with parchment paper.
2. In a mixing bowl, combine melted butter, eggs, pumpkin, almond milk, and vanilla. Mix until smooth and well combined.
3. In a separate bowl, combine almond flour, coconut flour, sweetener, baking powder, cinnamon, nutmeg, ginger, cloves, and salt. Stir in 1/4 cup of the walnuts if using.
4. Pour the wet ingredients into the dry ingredients. Stir well until combined.
5. Spoon batter into lined loaf pan. Sprinkle with remaining walnuts (optional: sprinkle a bit of sweetener and cinnamon over the nuts).
6. Bake 1 hour and 15 minutes. I suggest covering the bread with aluminum foil to prevent over browning. Cooking time may vary, the bread is done when a toothpick inserted comes out clean.

The pumpkin bread can be loosely covered and left out overnight, or refrigerate leftovers for up to five days, or slice and freeze for a month or two.

Nutritional Information:
Serving Size: 1/12 loaf Calories: 272 Fat: 25g Carbohydrates: 4g net Protein: 8g

This Creamy Beef Brisket Green Bean Casserole is what you are going to want on your Thanksgiving table this year. I promise everyone is going to love it!

This recipe is made 100% from scratch. The cream sauce is made with @carnivorecrisps Beef Brisket, shallots, garlic, mushrooms, and cream. Topped with a chicken flour Parmesan cheese topping and crispy onion rings that have been coated in chicken flour and fried.

Having the extra protein from the beef brisket and chicken flour makes this dish decadent and delicious. It’s easy to make and always a crowd favorite.

USE CODE: DEB at Carnivore Crisps

Ingredients:
2 lbs fresh green beans, trimmed
1 package Carnivore Crisps Beef Brisket Crisps, roughly chopped
1 lb button mushrooms, sliced
2 shallots, sliced
4 garlic cloves, minced
1 Tbsp butter
1 pint heavy whipping cream

Cheesy Chicken Topping:
1/4 cup Chicken Flour
1/4 cup Parmesan Cheese
2 Tbsp butter, melted
Mix all together. Set aside.

Onion Rings:
1/2 onion, sliced in 1/4-inch thick slices
1 egg
1/4 cup Carnivore Crisps Chicken Flour
2 Tbsp Parmesan Cheese
Olive oil for frying

Directions:
1. Blanch green beans by cooking in boiling water for 3 to 4 minutes, drain, and place in a bowl of ice water.
2. Once green beans are cooled, drain well and set aside.
3. Make onion rings. Mix together the chicken flour and Parmesan cheese in a bowl. In a separate bowl, whisk the egg. Dip the sliced onions in the whisked egg. Dredge in the chicken flour mixture. Fry onion rings in olive oil. Drain on paper towel. Set aside.
4. Make the cream sauce. In a large skillet heat butter until melted. Add brisket, heat for one minute. Remove the brisket.
5. To the skillet, add in shallot and garlic. Saute 5 minutes. Add in mushrooms. Cook until mushrooms are golden brown, about 10 minutes.
6. Add in one pint of heavy cream and cook down until it thickens. Add the beef brisket back to the pan and mix well. Add green beans to the cream sauce, stir until coated.
7. Place the green bean mixture into a baking dish. Top with cheesy chicken topping, extra chopped beef brisket, and onion rings. Bake at 350 degrees for 25 minutes.

MAKE AHEAD TURKEY GRAVY

When hosting a big Thanksgiving feast I like to have as many shortcuts as I can so it lessens the stress and I can enjoy the day too! I discovered several years ago that making your Turkey Gravy ahead of time is a huge time saver, and less mess in the kitchen on the day of the feast.

How To Make:
* Purchase turkey parts - thighs, wings, legs, even a small breast (I use 4 to 6 chicken wings, 4 legs, 2 thighs)
* Add to roasting a pn with 6 stalks of celery (cut into thirds), and 3 onions (quatered)
* Season generously with cracked black pepper, coarse pink salt
* Roast the turkey and veggies in the oven for 1 hour to 1 1/2  hours, or until golden brown
* Transfer everything into big stock pot (meat, bones, and veggies)
* Add in 32 ounces turkey broth and 5 cups water to the stock pot
* Simmer 1 to 2 hours hours until the meat falls off the bone. Strain the meat and veggies and your left a ton of delicious broth.
* Time To Make The Gravy by whiskin in roux made with flour (or xanthan gum for lowcarb), season with salt and pepper. Make up to 5 days in advance.

You can freeze for about 2 months if you real proactive! I made mine today - 2 1/2 weeks prior to Turkey Day

Give it try - I've been doing this for the past 6 or 7 years. And it's such a time saver. And the gravy is delicious!

When it’s time to prepare something extra super special, this healthy sweet squash casserole is it and will be a star. It is a decadently delicious side dish. Sweet, moist, and creamy squash, topped with a sweet brown pecan streusel. It's one of my favorites on Thanksgiving!

 I made fun twist on the traditional butternut squash casserole and I added in a peanut butter squash as well. Yes, there is such a thing as a peanut butter squash! It has a wonderful nutty flavor that paired amazingly well with the butternut squash.

This side dish is a winner! And it's easy to make in advance. Recipe follows:

Filling:
4 Tbsp butter melted
2 lbs. peeled and cubed butternut squash
1 lb. peeled and cubed peanut butter squash
½ cup half and half
¼ cup @swervesweetie brown sweetener
1 tsp vanilla extract
½ tsp kosher salt
2 eggs

Topping:
½ cup @grainfreeplanet Multi-use Baking Mix (Use Code: DEB10)
½ cup @swervesweetie brown sweetener
4 Tbsp butter melted
¼ tsp salt
¾ cup chopped pecans

Directions:
1. Preheat the oven to 350º F. Lightly spray a 2-quart baking dish with cooking spray.
2. Add butternut squash, and peanut butter squash to a large pot of salted water. Bring to a boil over high heat, then lower the heat to a simmer and cook until the squash is tender, 15 to 20 minutes. Drain (very well) and cool.
3. Place the drained squash in a bowl, and mash with potato masher.
4. In a large bowl, whisk together melted butter, brown sweetener, vanilla, salt, and eggs. Add in the mashed squash and mix well. Transfer to the prepared baking dish.
5. For the topping: in a medium bowl, combine the mulit-use bakery mix, brown sweetener, melted butter, and salt until moist, and the mixture clumps together. Stir in the pecans. Spread the mixture over the top of the squash.
Bake for 45 minutes covered. Uncover and bake another 10 minutes until topping is golden.

ASPARAGUS AU GRATIN

This Cheesy Asparagus au Gratin is sure to wow your family and guests this holiday season! Use the best ingredients to make this - using the freshest asparagus and good quality cheeses. To make you simply blanch the asparagus, place in a casserole dish, top with a decadent cheese sauce, and then bake in the oven.

Make Ahead Tips:
* Buy your asparagus a few days in advance: To keep asparagus fresh, trim bottoms, place in a cup or tall glass that has 1/2 inch of water in it, lightly cover the asparagus with a light weight plastic bag or plastic wrap.
* Blanch asparagus and store, covered, in the fridge. Make cheese sauce ahead, store in fridge, then warm on the stove top. When ready to make, assemble and bake.

1 lb asparagus, cleaned and trimmed
3 Tbsp butter
1 shallot, minced
1 cup heavy cream
1/8 tsp freshly grated nutmeg
salt and fresh cracked black pepper to taste
1/2 cup Parmesan cheese
1 cup shredded Fontina or Gruyere cheese

Topping:
1/4 cup Parmesan cheese
1 tsp Sweet paprika

1. Heat oven to 375 degrees F.
2. Blanch asparagus: Bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add the asparagus to the boiling water and cook until bright green and crisp-tender, about 3 minutes. Using a slotted spoon, transfer the asparagus to an ice water bath. Remove and drain on paper towels.
3. Arrange the asparagus in a buttered 13 x 9-inch baking dish
4. Make your sauce, in a medium size sauce pan, melt butter, add in shallot, cook until softened.
5. Slowly pour in heavy cream and heat until a light simmer. Stir in cheeses and heat until just melted.
6. Pour cheese sauce over the asparagus. Top with parmesan cheese and sweet paprika.
7. Bake for 30 minutes until bubbly.

Serve and Enjoy!

CRAB STUFFED SHRIMP

You all are going to want to make these Crab Stuffed Shrimp! These decadent shrimp are stuffed with crab and seasoned cracker crumbs. Then baked in a buttery wine sauce.

I used almond flour crackers, making the stuffing lowcarb and gluten-free, but feel free to use whatever crackers you like (Ritz, Saltines,etc.). And don't fear, they really are easy to prepare.

I make ahead and freeze. Then, on the day of your dinner or party, place the frozen stuffed shrimp in a baking dish, pour on the buttery wine sauce, pop in the oven, bake, and enjoy! 

You and your guests will LOVE these Crab Stuffed Shrimp! 🦀 🍤 🍽

Ingredients:
2 lbs. peeled, deveined, tails on jumbo shrimp
3 cans lump crab meat, drained @bumblebeefood
2 Tbsp butter
2 finely chopped green onions
1 clove garlic, minced
1/3 cup minced green bell pepper
1 jalapeno pepper, minced (optional)
1/4 tsp garlic powder
1 Tbsp dijon mustard
1 dash cayenne pepper
1/2 cup low crab cracker crumbs
1/4 cup mayonnaise
1 egg
2 Tbsp fresh parsley
1/2 juiced lemon
Topping:
1/4 cup butter, melted
1/4 cup dry white wine (or lemon juice)

Directions:
1. Make the stuffing - melt 2 Tbsp butter in a skillet and then add in the green onions  and peppers, and saute for 3-4 minutes. Then, add garlic and cook for about a minute. Remove from heat and let cool to room temperature.
2. In a separate bowl, add cracker crumbs and vegetable mixture (including all the butter drippings). Mix in 1 egg and mayonnaise.
3. Prepare the shrimp, cut along the length of the inside of the shrimp without cutting all the way through. Flatten the shrimp with the tail pointing up and place in a baking dish with the newly cut side facing up.
4. Scoop a tablespoon of stuffing into a mound on the shrimp’s flat part. Then, bake for about 20 minutes. (Note: Can be frozen prior to baking - bake time will be longer if frozen).
5. In a microwave safe bow), melt 1/4 cup butter. Remove from microwave, stir in 1/4 cup dry white wine. Pour over shrimp. Bake for 20 minutes, or until shrimp are just pink.

PUMPKIN CHIFFON PIE

Impress your family at Thanksgiving with this Pumpkin Chiffon Pie. It is a lighter, airier version of traditional pumpkin pie. This is a no bake pie in such that the filling is cooked on the stove top & cooled, then you fold in a meringue into the cooked pumpkin filling that has been stabilized with unflavored gelatin. This makes for a light, airy pie filling. Marry this pie filling with a gingerbread cookie pie crust, and you've got yourself a winner!

Ingredients:
1 Pumpkin Spice Pie Crust (see recipe)
1 cup Allulose sweetener @RxSugar
1 envelope unflavored gelatin
1 1/2 teaspoons pumpkin pie spice
1/2 tsp. salt
1 (15-oz) can pumpkin puree @libbyspumpkin
3 egg yolks
3 egg whites
1/2 cup heavy whipping cream
1/4 tsp. cream of tartar

 Gingerbread Cookie Pie Crust:
6 oz  Gingerbread Cookie Clusters by @lollis_clusters_dba_momz_nutz
3 Tbsp melted butter
1. Pulverize  Gingerbread Cookie Clusters. Pour into a medium mixing bowl.
2. Mix in melted butter into the pulverized cookie clusters until combined.
3. Press into the bottom of a 9-inch glass pie pan.
4. Bake at 350 degrees for 10 minutes or until crust is set.

Pumpkin Chiffon Filling:
1. In a medium saucepan, whisk together 3/4 cup sweetener, gelatin, pumpkin pie spice, and salt.
2. In a bowl, whisk together the pumpkin, egg yolks, and heavy cream until smooth. Pour into the sauce pan with the sweetened mixture.
3. Place saucepan over medium heat, stirring constantly, until mixture is hot and small bubbles are starting to form around the edges. Remove from heat, transfer to a large bowl, cool to room temperature.
4. When the filling has cooled, beat the egg whites until soft peaks form. Continue beating, gradually adding the remaining 1/4 cup of sweetener (1 tablespoon at a time) until stiff peaks form.
5. Gently fold the egg whites into the pumpkin mixture, pour it into the cooled pie shell.
6. Refrigerate at least 4 hours or overnight until firm, then top with sweetened whipped cream & dust with cinnamon.

These easy Turkey Croquettes feature a creamy filling of turkey coated in a crispy shell for delicious way to use up those Thanksgiving turkey leftovers.

If you're not familiar with a croquette, they are a deep-fried roll originating in French cuisine, consisting a of a binder combined with a a filling which is then coated or breaded.
These croquettes are made with chopped turkey, cream cheese, onions and celery, and twice coated with @carnivorecrisps chicken flour for one delicious tapa, appetizer, game day snack, or meal!

That crispy outside and creamy inside is irresistible. Make a bunch and freeze so you always have them on hand. Serve as is, with gravy, cranberry sauce, or a Velouté Sauce.

FOLLOW FOR MORE DELICIOUS RECIPES!

Ingredients:
2 cups chopped cooked turkey
4 oz cream cheese, softened
1 Tbsp mayonnaise (could use softened butter)
1 Tbsp minced onion
2 Tbsp minced celery
salt & pepper taste

Note: the celery are onion are optional

Coating:
1 egg
1/3 to 1/2 cup chicken flour, @carnivorecrisps (USE CODE: DEB)

Directions:

These lowcarb Peanut Butter Snickerdoodles melt in your mouth.

They're full of peanut butter and cinnamon flavor. Perfect to eat anytime, but even more so during the holidays. These are one of my favorite traditional cookies that I made sugar-free and grain-free using @grainfreeplant 's Multi-Use Baker Mix, natural peanut butter, butter, and sweetener. Peanut Butter Snickerdoodles

Ingredients:
3/4 cup  Muti-Use Bakery Mix, @grainfreeplant (USE CODE: DEB10)
3/4 cup granular monkfuit sweetener
1 tsp cinnamon
1 cup natural peanut butter
1 stick butter, softened

One being these Mini Quiche Lorraine. They are absolutely delicious. You can make crustless or with your favorite pie crust (regular, gluten-free, or lowcarb). Ingredients:
8 eggs
3/4 cup heavy whipping cream
2 oz cream cheese
1 1/2 cups shredded Swiss cheese
1 cup @samsclub Real Crumbled Bacon
1 small onion, chopped
salt and black pepper to taste

Yields approximately 16 jumbo muffin size quiche

Directions:
In a pan, cook the crumbled bacon just until crisp. Remove bacon, reserving any bacon fat. Add in the onion and saute until softened. Remove the onion and add in with the bacon you set aside.

In a large bowl, mix together, heavy cream, and cream cheese (breaking up the cream cheese into bite size pieces). Add Swiss cheese, bacon and onion, salt, and pepper. Stir until combined.

If Making With Crust:
Cut crust into 4-inch circles and place in the jumbo muffin pan.Making sure the crust goes up the sides of each cup. Pre-bake for 5 minutes (timing depends on the type of crust you use). Remove from the oven. Fill each muffin cup with egg mixture until almost reaches the top of the crust. Bake at 350 degrees for 20 minutes or until center of each is just set. Note: the quiche will rise while baking, but will settle as it cools.

If Making Crust-less:
Spray muffin pan with cooking spray. Fill each muffin cup 3/4 full with egg mixture. (You will repeat several times depending on the size of your pan). Bake at 350 degrees for 20 minutes or until center of each is just set. Note: the quiche will rise while baking, but will settle as it cools.

To store for later:
Cool the mini quiche. Store in an air tight container in the freezer for up to 1 month. I layer the quiche with wax paper in a large container.

To Reheat:
Place in a 350 degree oven for 8 to 10 minutes.

CHEESY CRAB STUFFED GOUGERES (aka Savory Cream Puffs) is my way to start out 2024!

I've been waiting, and waiting, and waiting to share this recipe with you all! 

Earlier this year you all (hopefully) saw my magical lowcarb cream puffs that I made with @grainfreeplanet pasta mix stuffed with cream filling. They were my favorite recipe for 2023 - the most delightful lowcarb treat of all time! When I made these, I immediately put in the back of my brain that I needed to make a savory cream puff.

So for 2024 I reveal Cheesy Crab Stuffed Gougeres (small pastry made with Choux dough mixed with cheese) using the same method. Very easy to make. Just whip the cheesy cream puffs/Gougeres. Let cool completely, and then stuffe each with a cheesy crab filling! Bake & Serve.

You can make ahead, freeze, and reheat.

FOLLOW ME @deb.makes.lowcarb.delish SO YOU DON'T MISS OUT ON MY LOWCARB RECIPES

Grouges Choux Pastry:
2 eggs
1/2 cup plus 2 tbsp water
2/3 cup @grainfreeplanet Quick and Easy Pasta Mix (use code: DEB10)
3 Tbsp grated cheddar cheese

Crab Filling Filling:
4 oz cream cheese softened
1/4 cup Swiss cheese
2 Tbsp mayonnaise
4 oz Louis Kemp Crab Delights
1 garlic cloves minced
2 tbsp minced green onion
1 tsp Worcestershire sauce
1/2 tsp Dijon mustard
1 tsp lemon juice

Make Puffs:
1. Blend all ingredients together in a hand blender. Pour into a bowl and let sit 15 to 20 minutes.
2. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Drop heaping tablespoons of mix onto the parchment paper, shaping a bit so they are round and somewhat mounded. Sprinkle with cheddar cheese over each.
3. Bake at 325 degrees for 18 minutes. At this point remove pan from the oven, gently poke a hole with a toothpick in each puff.
4. Place back in the oven another 10-13 minutes until golden. Turn off oven, leave puffs in the oven for another 15 minutes. They should be golden and crisp and sound hollow when you tap on them. Allow to cool completely.
Make Filling:
In a bowl, mix together all crab filling ingredients.
Assemble:
Slice each puff in half, place filling on bottom half of each pastry, place tops over the filling. Place the filled pastries unto a aking sheet. Bake 325 for 10 mins.

Let's get this year started with delicious healthy foods! This Sheet Pan Pork Tenderloin Roast with Vegetables recipe is sure to be a hit for Sunday suppers! The combination of juicy pork and flavorful vegetables, along with the ease of preparation and cleanup, makes it a winning recipe.

FOLLOW me for more delicious meal ideas and recipes!

This recipe is perfect for a relaxing Sunday supper with the family and will surely leave you with mouthwatering flavors and minimal cleanup. Enjoy!

Ingredients:
⅓ cup apple cider vinegar
⅓ cup olive oil
¼ cup soy sauce or coconut aminos
¼ cup Dijon grain mustard
sprig of rosemary (can sub in dried rosemary)
1 tsp black pepper
1 - 2lb pork tenderloin
Vegetables (carrots, red onion, potato, Brussels sprouts)

Directions:
1. In a bowl, whisk together the apple cider vinegar, olive oil, soy sauce (or coconut aminos), Dijon mustard, and black pepper to create the marinade.
2. Place the pork tenderloin in a large freezer bag and pour the marinade over it. Add a sprig of fresh rosemary to the bag. Seal the bag and let the pork marinate in the refrigerator for at least 1 hour, or overnight for best flavor.
3. Once the marinating time is complete, remove the pork tenderloin from the fridge and allow it to come to room temperature. This step helps the pork cook more evenly.
4. Preheat the oven to 375°F (190°C).
5. Heat a couple of tablespoons of olive oil over high heat in a pan. Sear all sides of the pork tenderloin until golden brown.
6. Transfer the seared pork to a baking sheet or baking pan.
7. Arrange the prepared vegetables (carrots, red onions, Brussels sprouts, and any other vegetables you like) around the pork on the baking sheet.
8. Pour the reserved marinade over the pork and the vegetables.
9. Place the baking sheet in the preheated oven and bake at 375°F for about 45 minutes, or until the internal temperature of the pork reaches 145°F.
10. Once done, remove the sheet pan from the oven and allow the pork to rest for a few minutes before slicing.
11. Serve the sliced pork tenderloin with the roasted vegetables and enjoy your flavorful and easy-to-make meal!

Ingredients:
1 large eggplant
Peanut stuffing:
1/4 cup skinned peanuts
1 Tbsp Green Curry @masimasaspice
1 tbsp ground coriander seeds
1 tbsp ground cumin seeds
4 large cloves garlic crushed
2 tsp ginger grated
½ tsp red chili powder
2 tbsp sugar-free tomato ketchup
1 tsp salt
2 tsp sweetener (@RxSugar Allulose)
1/8 tsp baking soda
3 tbsp olive oil
Tomato sauce:
1 Tbsp olive oil
½ tsp mustard seeds
½ tsp cumin seeds
1 cup chopped tomatoes

Directions:
Prepare eggplant:

 - In a small food processor, add all of the ingredients for the stuffing except for the oil. Pulse until combined, and peanuts are still coarse.

I heard on the radio that today is National Bagel Day. So I dug out my Fathead Dough Bagel Recipe that I came up in 2017. And dang, 7 years later that same recipe still works like a charm, and these  totally hit the spot. Especially the blueberry one - I sliced and topped with cream cheese. Yum!

This recipe contains yeast, which really started out for flavor when I made thee back in the day. But today I got busy and left the unbaked bagels on top of my warm oven, and they actually proofed a bit, making them airy on no so dense.

These toast up wonderfully and are great with butter and cream cheese, or use to make you favorite sandwich.

Low Carb Bagels (using Yeast)
Makes: 8 Bagels/5G Net Carbs
Dough:
3 cups shredded mozzarella (I used prepacked reduced fat cheese)
2 cups almond flour
2 tsp xanthan gum
4 Tbsp cream cheese
2 eggs
1 packet Rapid Rise Yeast
2 Tbsp of warm water

Toppings :
2 Tbsp Melted butter
Sesame seeds
Poppy seeds
Dried Onion Flakes
Dill Weed
Caraway Seeds
Sweetener & Cinnamon
Everything But The Bagel
Pretzel Salt
Parmesan Cheese& Garlic Powder
Jalapeno Peppers (chop 3 or 4 peppers and and mix the peppers into individual bagels, after you divide the dough)
Frozen Blueberries (add 6 to 8 berries into individual bagels, after you divide the dough)

Preparation:
1. Preheat oven to 350°
2. Dissolve the yeast in the warm water and allow it to sit and activate for 2 minutes.
3. In a small/med bowl mix together the almond flour and xanthan gum.
4. Place the mozzarella and cream cheese in a medium bowl, microwave 1 minute. Take out and stir, microwave 1 more minute or until cheeses are melted.
5.Remove bowl from microwave. Add the almond flour mixture to the melted cheeses. Mix a bit, then add yeast mixture and mix until incorporated. Add eggs, one at time, mixing until combined. I then kneaded the dough on the counter for a few minutes until it was well combined. Form a ball from the dough. Cut into 8 equal portions.
6. Roll each portion of dough into log shapes and then make a donut shape from each log. Place on baking sheet.
7.Brush bagels with butter and sprinkle on toppings.
8. Bake at 350 degrees for 15-18 minutes.

Thai Red Curry Chicken

Let's make homemade Thai red curry chicken tonight! Tender chicken, vibrant bell peppers, and aromatic spices all simmered in creamy coconut milk. This Thai red curry chicken is packed with lean protein, colorful veggies, and the perfect balance of exotic spices.

Who says healthy eating can't be delicious?

Be sure to LIKE & SAVE this recipe

FOLLOW ME for more weeknight healthy meals

Ingredients:
- 1 lb chicken breast, sliced into thin strips
- 3 cloves garlic, minced
- 1 small onion, sliced
- 2-3 tablespoons red curry paste
- 1 tablespoon ginger, grated
- 1 can (14 oz) coconut milk
- 1 red bell pepper, sliced
- 1 green bell pepper, sliced
- 1 green bell pepper, sliced
- 1 tablespoons olive oil
- 1 tablespoons fish sauce (optional for seasoning)
- 2 tablespoons brown sweetener (optional for sweetness)
- Fresh Thai basil leaves for garnish (can use Italian basil)
- Cooked cauliflower rice for serving

Instructions:
1. Heat the olive oil in a large skillet or wok over medium heat. Add the chicken and cook through. Remove and set aside.
2. To the same pan, add the minced garlic and sliced onion, and sauté for 1-2 minutes until the onion becomes translucent.
3. Add the red curry paste and grated ginger to the skillet and stir-fry for about 1 minute until fragrant.
4. Pour in the coconut milk and stir well to combine with the curry mixture. Bring the mixture to a gentle boil, then reduce the heat to low and let it simmer for 10-15 minutes, stirring occasionally.
5. Add chicken and sliced bell peppers to the skillet and continue to simmer for 20 minutes until the peppers are tender but still slightly crisp. Add in the fresh basil.
6. If using, season the curry with fish sauce for saltiness and/or brown sweetener for sweetness. Adjust the seasoning to your taste.
7. Remove the skillet from the heat.
8. Serve the Thai red curry chicken over cooked cauliflower rice, and garnish with fresh basil leaves if desired.

Enjoy your homemade Thai red curry chicken!

🍕 Low-Carb Detoit-Style 🍕

Craving pizza? Me too! I had my first Detroit-Style pizza a few years, and today I really want one! If you're not familiar with Detroit Style Pizza, it's a rectangular pizza with thick crust that is crispy and chewy (kind of a crispy fried bottom) that is overflowing with melty cheese. It is traditionally topped with Wisconsin Brick cheese (I used mozzarella & jack cheese), which caramelizes against the sides of the rectangular pan.

So, if you want to save on some carbs, this is a guilt-free indulgence you will love.

SAVE, LIKE, and FOLLOW!!

For The Dough, you will need:
1 2/3 cups @kingarthurbaking Keto Wheat Flour
3/4 cup water, cool
1 teaspoon instant yeast
1/2 teaspoon table salt
1 tablespoon olive oil, plus more for greasing the pan
1 teaspoon King Arthur Pizza Dough Flavor, optional
Directions: On King Arthur 🤴 website

For The Toppings:
1/2 cup pizza sauce (recipe on my blog)
12 oz. Wisconsin Brick cheese (or a combination of mozzarella &  Monterey Jack cheeses)
Pepperoni (any favorite pizza topping)

Assemble Pizza:
1. Make the pizza dough according to directions.
2. Pour 1 tablespoon of olive oil in a 9×13-inch baking pan and spread it around. Add the dough to the center.
3. Press the dough, using your fingers, working it close to the edge of the pan, but not all the way.
4. Spread the pizza sauce on top of the pizza dough, smoothing it out until it reaches the edges. This pizza doesn’t really have a crust exterior, so be sure to take it to the edges.
5. Top it with the shredded cheese(s) all the way to the edge of the pan. (important step).
6. Add the pepperoni -a nice blanket of 'ronis makes the best 😋
7. Place in preheated 450 degree oven. Bake 20-30 minutes until edges are golden brown and the cheese is all melty and bubbling.
